Hello there,

This is a small update to the DesktopGL gamepad database to support Xbox One S controllers over bluetooth on Linux (it was already working on Mac OS and Windows, but was missing from Linux).

@tomspilman @KonajuGames

It seems, for some reason, that `BasicEffect` is behaving differently when looping on each `Techniques` and using the `CurrentTechnique` property. The following code shows the problem:

```
GraphicsDevice.Clear(Color.CornflowerBlue);

VertexPosition[] vertices = new VertexPosition[3];

vertices[0] = new VertexPosition(new Vector3(-0.5f, -0.25f, 0f));
vertices[1] = new VertexPosition(new Vector3(0.0f, (float)Math.Sqrt(0.75) - 0.25f, 0f));
vertices[2] = new VertexPosition(new Vector3(0.5f, -0.25f, 0f));

BasicEffect basicEffect = new BasicEffect(this.GraphicsDevice);

basicEffect.EmissiveColor = Color.White.ToVector3();
basicEffect.LightingEnabled = true;

basicEffect.Projection = Matrix.CreateOrthographic(this.GraphicsDevice.Viewport.Bounds.Width, this.GraphicsDevice.Viewport.Bounds.Height, -100, 100);
basicEffect.World = Matrix.CreateScale(100f);

// This renders the triangle white, as expected
foreach (EffectPass pass in basicEffect.CurrentTechnique.Passes)
{
	pass.Apply();

	GraphicsDevice.DrawUserPrimitives(PrimitiveType.TriangleList, vertices, 0, 1);
}
// */

/* This renders the triangle black
foreach (EffectTechnique technique in basicEffect.Techniques)
{
	foreach (EffectPass pass in technique.Passes)
	{
		pass.Apply();

		this.GraphicsDevice.DrawUserPrimitives(PrimitiveType.TriangleList, vertices, 0, 1);
	}
}
// */
```

Using `CurrentTechnique` is giving the expected result, but looping each `Techniques` renders the triangle black. What I find weird is that `BasicEffect` is just holding one technique, so the loop is only on one element, the technique named `"BasicEffect"`.

Am I missing something, or is it a bug?

This is a proposal for the implementation and discussion, of a irregular rectangle draw call or in reality a spritebatched quad type draw overload to be added to spritebatch. 

I had previously mentioned this on the wishlist http://community.monogame.net/t/monogame-feature-wishlist/6850/171 , there has been some speak of it here and there on occasion but i wanted to make a formalized request for it here.

This would add to the functionality of spritebatch in a big way with a small change.

Essentially you would gain the ability to have things like trapzoids rombus ect and irregular 2d geometric draws. This would be done like any existing spriteBatch.Draw( ... ) call does currently.

<img src="https://qph.ec.quoracdn.net/main-qimg-98166276b744a923fb269438244e2d96" alt="">

Since this functionality is natural to these classes it is very easy to add it.

Some (untested) psuedo code is given (_which is less pesudo code then it is a trimmed down existing Draw call_) with different paremeters. Additionally this example shows a addition of a Third set(...) method in SpriteBatchItem which this draw call would use.

```

        // In SpriteBatch
        // https://github.com/MonoGame/MonoGame/blob/develop/MonoGame.Framework/Graphics/SpriteBatch.cs

        /// <summary>
        /// Submit a sprite for drawing in the current batch.
        /// Altered for irregular shaped rectangles i.e. quads.
        /// Shows eliminations for a more functional draw.
        /// It might be nice to have color 0 1 2 3 but that would fatten it up a bit more
        /// </summary>
        public void Draw(
            Texture2D texture,
            Vector2 TL, Vector2 TR, Vector2 BR, Vector2 BL,
            Rectangle? sourceRectangle,
            Color color,
            float layerDepth)
        {
            CheckValid(texture);

            var item = _batcher.CreateBatchItem();
            item.Texture = texture;

            // set SortKey based on SpriteSortMode.
            switch (_sortMode)
            {
                // Comparison of Texture objects.
                case SpriteSortMode.Texture:
                    item.SortKey = texture.SortingKey;
                    break;
                // Comparison of Depth
                case SpriteSortMode.FrontToBack:
                    item.SortKey = layerDepth;
                    break;
                // Comparison of Depth in reverse
                case SpriteSortMode.BackToFront:
                    item.SortKey = -layerDepth;
                    break;
            }

            // Source rectangle could be kept for efficiency instead of passing Vector uv's
            // origin isn't needed now.
            if (sourceRectangle.HasValue)
            {
                var srcRect = sourceRectangle.GetValueOrDefault();
                _texCoordTL.X = srcRect.X * texture.TexelWidth;
                _texCoordTL.Y = srcRect.Y * texture.TexelHeight;
                _texCoordBR.X = (srcRect.X + srcRect.Width) * texture.TexelWidth;
                _texCoordBR.Y = (srcRect.Y + srcRect.Height) * texture.TexelHeight;
            }
            else
            {
                _texCoordTL = Vector2.Zero;
                _texCoordBR = Vector2.One;
            }

            // We dont need SpriteEffects when manually passing vertices.
            // We are responsible for passing them in the order we desire.
            // We can just pass the vertices in different orders to replace SpriteEffects

            // We do however need a additional set overloaded method in SpriteBatchItem.cs

            item.Set
                (
                TL,
                TR,
                BL,
                BR,
                color,
                _texCoordTL,
                _texCoordBR,
                layerDepth
                );

            FlushIfNeeded();
        }

        // in  MonoGame/MonoGame.Framework/Graphics/SpriteBatchItem.cs
        // https://github.com/MonoGame/MonoGame/blob/develop/MonoGame.Framework/Graphics/SpriteBatchItem.cs#L60

        
        public void Set(Vector2 TL, Vector2 TR, Vector2 BL, Vector2 BR, Color color, Vector2 texCoordTL, Vector2 texCoordBR, float depth)
        {
            vertexTL.Position.X = TL.X;
            vertexTL.Position.Y = TL.Y;
            vertexTL.Position.Z = depth;
            vertexTL.Color = color;
            vertexTL.TextureCoordinate.X = texCoordTL.X;
            vertexTL.TextureCoordinate.Y = texCoordTL.Y;

            vertexTR.Position.X = TR.X;
            vertexTR.Position.Y = TR.Y;
            vertexTR.Position.Z = depth;
            vertexTR.Color = color;
            vertexTR.TextureCoordinate.X = texCoordBR.X;
            vertexTR.TextureCoordinate.Y = texCoordTL.Y;

            vertexBL.Position.X = BL.X;
            vertexBL.Position.Y = BL.Y;
            vertexBL.Position.Z = depth;
            vertexBL.Color = color;
            vertexBL.TextureCoordinate.X = texCoordTL.X;
            vertexBL.TextureCoordinate.Y = texCoordBR.Y;

            vertexBR.Position.X = BR.X;
            vertexBR.Position.Y = BR.Y;
            vertexBR.Position.Z = depth;
            vertexBR.Color = color;
            vertexBR.TextureCoordinate.X = texCoordBR.X;
            vertexBR.TextureCoordinate.Y = texCoordBR.Y;
        }
```

My personal foremost functional use for this would be text related.
However im sure that many creative people would find unforeseeable uses for such functionality.

http://community.monogame.net/t/fastest-way-to-draw-lots-of-simple-mesh-as-possable/9413

Anyways i posted this for any thoughts comments or just to show the basic premise of the simplicity of the code changes involved.
